[[File:Azerbaijani Girl.jpg|thumb|upright|A girl in [[Khachmaz (city)|Khachmaz]].]]
From the total population of about 8 million people as of April 2006, there were 4,380,000 (nearly 51%) city dwellers and a rural population of 4,060,000 (49%).<ref name="SEX">{{cite web| last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Population | work = | publisher = Azerbaijan Gender Information Center| date = | url = http://www.gender-az.org/shablon_en.shtml?doc/en/about/country| format =| doi = | accessdate = 2007-05-27 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070510154101/http://gender-az.org/shablon_en.shtml?doc/en/about/country  |archivedate = 2007-05-10}}</ref> 51% of the total population were female.<ref name="SEX"/> The [[sex ratio]] for total population in that year was therefore 0.94 males per female.<ref name="DEM">{{cite web| last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Population and Demographics | work = | publisher = Intute| date = | url = http://www.intute.ac.uk/sciences/worldguide/html/819_people.html| doi = | accessdate = 2007-05-27}}</ref>

The 2006 [[population growth]] rate was 0.66%, compared to 1.14% worldwide.<ref name="DEM"/> A significant factor restricting the population growth is rather a high level of [[Human migration|migration]]. As many as 3 million Azeris, many of them guest workers, live in [[Russia]].<ref>[http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/rights/articles/eav111102.shtml Azerbaijan Acts to Limit the Discrimination Against Azeris in Russia] by Nailia Sohbetqizi. ''Eurasianet.org''. 11 November 2002. Retrieved 15 September 2006.</ref> In 2006 Azerbaijan saw migration of <U+2212>4.38/1,000 persons.<ref name="DEM"/> With 800,000 refugees and IDPs, Azerbaijan has the largest [[Internally displaced person|internally displaced population]] in the region, and, as of 2006, had the highest per capita IDP population in the world.<ref>[http://www.unicef.org/ceecis/Azerbaijan.pdf Education in Azerbaijan] ([[PDF]]). [[UNICEF]].</ref>

The highest morbidity in 2005 was from [[respiratory disease]]s (806.9 diseases per 10,000 of total population).<ref>{{cite web| last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Population morbidity by main diseases groups | work = | publisher = The Ministry of Health | date = | url = http://www.mednet.az/index1en.htm| doi = | accessdate = 2007-05-27}}</ref> In 2005, the highest morbidity for [[infectious disease|infectious]] and [[List of human parasitic diseases|parasitic diseases]] was noted among [[influenza]] and [[Common cold|acute respiratory infections]] (4168,2 per 100,000 population).<ref>{{cite web| last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Morbidity of population by various infectious and parasitic diseases | work = | publisher = The Ministry of Health | date = | url = http://www.mednet.az/index1en.htm| doi = | accessdate = 2007-05-27}}</ref> 2007 estimate for total [[life expectancy]] is 66 years, 70.7 years for women and 61.9 for men.<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Azerbaijan Facts and Figures | work = | publisher = MSN Encarta | date = | url = http://encarta.msn.com/fact_631504718/Azerbaijan_Facts_and_Figures.html| doi = | accessdate = 2007-05-27|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5kwKuBqIg|archivedate=2009-10-31|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

The [[Azerbaijani diaspora]] is found in 42 countries<ref>{{Az icon}} {{cite web| last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Xaricd<U+0259>ki t<U+0259><U+015F>kilatlar | work = | publisher =Diaspora.az| date = | url = http://www.diaspora.gov.az/index.php?options=content&id=87| doi = | accessdate = 2007-05-25}}</ref> and in turn there are many centers for ethnic minorities inside Azerbaijan, including the German cultural society "Karelhaus", [[Slavic peoples|Slavic]] cultural center, Azerbaijani-[[Israeli Jews|Israeli]] community, [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] cultural center, International [[Talysh people|Talysh]] Association, [[Lezgins|Lezgin]] national center "Samur", Azerbaijani-[[Tatarstan|Tatar]] community, [[Crimean Tatars]] society, etc.<ref name="MIN">{{cite web| last = | first = | authorlink = | coauthors = | title =Ethnic minorities | work = | publisher =Ministry of Foreign Affairs| date = | url = http://www.mfa.gov.az/eng/foreign_policy/inter_affairs/human/ethnic.shtml| doi = | accessdate = 2007-05-27 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070417093650/http://www.mfa.gov.az/eng/foreign_policy/inter_affairs/human/ethnic.shtml  |archivedate = 2007-04-17}}</ref>
The ethnic composition of the population according to the 1999 population census: 90.6% [[Azerbaijani people|Azeris]], 2.2% [[Lezgins]], 1.8% [[Russians]], 1.5% [[Armenians]] (Almost all live in the break-away region of Nagorno-Karabakh), 1.0% [[Talysh people|Talysh]] (disputed as too low by Talysh nationalists),<ref>[http://www.cria-online.org/5_4.html Disputed number of Talysh in Azerbaijan].</ref><ref>[http://books.google.com/books?id=NwvoM-ZFoAgC&pg=PA674&lpg=PA674&dq=%22Talysh+nationalists%22&source=web&ots=8aLgM9V1qo&sig=_-x9bspkEfCVjmJDiavECJZAuKg&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=5&ct=result Reasons for the dispute around the number of Talysh in Azerbaijan]: ''One Europe, Many Nations: A Historical Dictionary of European National Groups'', by James Minahan, Greenwood, 2000,
ISBN 978-0-313-30984-7, ISBN 978-0-313-30984-7, p. 674 (viewable on [[Google Books]]).</ref> 0.6% [[Caucasian Avars|Avars]], 0.5% [[Turkish people|Turks]], 0.4% [[Tatars]], 0.4% [[Ukrainians]], 0.2% [[Tsakhur people|Tsakhur]], 0.2% [[Georgians]], 0.13% [[Kurdish people|Kurds]], 0.13% [[Tats]], 0.1% [[Jew]]s, 0.05% [[Udi people|Udins]], other 0.2%. Many Russians left Azerbaijan during the 1990s. According to the 1989 census, there were 392,000 ethnic [[Russians]] in Azerbaijan, or 5.6% of the population.<ref>[http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/insight/articles/pp083003.shtml Southern Caucasus: Facing Integration Problems, Ethnic Russians Long For Better Life]. EurasiaNet.org. August 30, 2003.</ref> According to the statistics, about 390,000 [[Armenians in Azerbaijan|Armenians]] lived in Azerbaijan in 1989.<ref>[http://www.uscis.gov/files/nativedocuments/azerba93.pdf Azerbaijan: The Status of Armenians, Russians, Jews and other minorities] ([[PDF]]). United States Citizenship and Immigration Services (USCIS).</ref>

Although [[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]] (also called ''Azeri'') is the most widely spoken language in the country and is spoken by about a quarter of the population of Iran, there are [[Languages of Azerbaijan|13 other languages]] spoken natively in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ethnologue.com/show_country.asp?name=AZ |title=Ethnologue report for Azerbaijan |publisher=Ethnologue.com |date= |accessdate=2009-01-03}}</ref> Some of these languages are very small communities, others are more vital.<ref>Clifton, John M., editor. 2002 (vol 1.), 2003 (vol. 2). ''Studies in languages of Azerbaijan''. Baku, Azerbaijan and Saint Petersburg, Russia: Institute of International Relations, Academy of Sciences of Azerbaijan and North Eurasian Group, SIL International.</ref> Azerbaijani is a [[Turkic languages|Turkic language]] which belongs to the [[Altaic languages|Altaic family]] and is mutually intelligible with [[Turkish language|Turkish]] and [[Gagauz language|Gagauz]]. The language is written with a [[Azerbaijani alphabet|modified Latin alphabet]] today, but was earlier written in the Arabic alphabet (until 1929), in the [[Uniform Turkic Alphabet]] (1929<U+2013>1939), and in the [[Cyrillic alphabet]] (1939<U+2013>1991).<ref>Hatcher, Lynley. 2008. Script change in Azerbaijan: acts of identity. ''International Journal of the Sociology of Language'' 192:105<U+2013>116.</ref> The changes in alphabet have been largely molded by religious and political forces.

[[Iranian Azerbaijanis]] are the largest minority in [[Iran]]. The CIA World Factbook estimates Iranian Azerbaijanis as comprising nearly 16 million, or 24% of Iran's population.<ref>CIA <U+2013> The World Factbook. [https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/ir.html CIA.gov] "Iran".</ref>

